We will work the Page Column

paren_match<-function(page,text) {
    start<-cpos(page,"(")
  end<-cpos(page,")")  
  if(!is.na(start) && !is.na(end)) {
    take_string_inside_brackets<-substring(page,start+1,end-1)  
    return(grepl(tolower(take_string_inside_brackets),tolower(text),fixed=TRUE)) 
  }else{
    return(FALSE)
  }
}

Understanding the above function 1. cpos function finds the 1st position in the string that you have provided. Here we have provided ( and ) characters. We need their position. It will return NA if it doesnt find

  1. if(!is.na(start) && !is.na(end)) { take_string_inside_brackets<-substring(page,start+1,end-1) What this above line does from the page column it will take a value(word) whose position is greater than start position by 1 and less than 1 by end position

3.the value that we get from the above code, we will take it and check if the same value(word) exists in text column. If yes then return TRUE Tolower means it will change the word and text to lower cases

GLM Model

Method 1 This accuracy is without spitting the data. The accuracy is considering the entire Train_data

Sfunction<-function(Satul)
{
  model<-glm(corr~Satul,family = binomial(link='logit'),data = Strain_Data)
  Strain_Data$prediction <- predict(model,newdata=Strain_Data,type='response')
  Strain_Data$fitted.results <- ifelse(Strain_Data$prediction > 0.6,1,0)
  
  Strain_Data$corralter<-ifelse(Strain_Data$corr=="True",1,0)
  misClasificError <- mean(Strain_Data$fitted.results != Strain_Data$corralter)
  
  print(paste('Accuracy',1-misClasificError))
}

Function

decision_tree <- function(dframe, name, dmodel, testset) {
  decision <- predict(dmodel,newdata= testset,type="class")
  Chandler<-ifelse(decision!="False","TRUE","FALSE")
  confusionMatrix<- table(Chandler, true=testset$corr)
  accuracy<-sum(diag(confusionMatrix)/sum(confusionMatrix))
  dframe <- rbind(dframe, data.frame(model=c(name), accuracy=c(accuracy)))
  return(dframe)
}
results1<- data.frame(matrix(ncol = 2, nrow = 0))

results1 <- decision_tree(results1, "body_score", rpart(corr ~ body_score,method="class",data=trainset), testset)

results1 <- decision_tree(results1, "obs_len", rpart(corr ~ obs_len,method="class",data=trainset), testset)
results1 <- decision_tree(results1, "score+len", rpart(corr ~ obs_len + body_score,method="class", data=trainset), testset)
results1 <- decision_tree(results1, "paren+len", rpart(corr ~ obs_len + paren_match,method="class", data=trainset), testset)
results1 <- decision_tree(results1, "paren_match", rpart(corr ~ paren_match,method="class", data=trainset), testset)
results1 <- decision_tree(results1, "score+paren_match", rpart(corr ~ scale_score + paren_match,method="class", data=trainset), testset)
results1 <- decision_tree(results1, "score+len+paren_match", rpart(corr ~ scale_len + scale_score + paren_match,method="class", data=trainset), testset)
results1 <- decision_tree(results1, "links", rpart(corr ~ inlinks,method="class", data=trainset), testset)
results1 <- decision_tree(results1, "loglinks", rpart(corr ~ log_links,method="class", data=trainset), testset)
results1 <- decision_tree(results1, "score+len+links+paren_match", rpart(corr ~ scale_len + scale_score + log_links + paren_match,method="class", data=trainset), testset)
results1 <- decision_tree(results1, "score+links+paren_match", rpart(corr ~ scale_len + scale_score + paren_match,method="class", data=trainset), testset)

SVM

  1. Radial SVM
SVM <- function(df, name, model, test) {
  svm.pred <- predict(model, test)
  svm.table <- table(pred = svm.pred, true=test$corr)
  df <- rbind(df, data.frame(model=c(name), score=c(classAgreement(svm.table)$diag)))
  return(df)
}

Question 3:

3(a)

Improving Predictions

Ways to Improve the classifier:

  1. SVM and Decision Tree give almost same result but decision tree is more reliable and its performance can be enhanced using ensemble methods, where many trees are fit and predictions are aggregated accross trees.

2.Amongst these ensemble methods, we choose Random Forest for improving the predictions

Random Forest is chosen as a classifier to improve the prediction because:

Random Forest produces large number of decision trees. This approach first takes a random sample of data and identifies a key set of features to grow each decision tree. These decision trees then have their OUt of Bag error determined. Then collection of decision trees are compared to find joint set of variables that creates strongest classification model.

Creating a function for Random forest

randomf <- function(dframe, name, dmodel, testset) {
  decision <- predict(dmodel,newdata= testset,type="class")
  Chandler<-ifelse(decision!="False","TRUE","FALSE")
  confusionMatrix<- table(Chandler, true=testset$corr)
  accuracy<-sum(diag(confusionMatrix)/sum(confusionMatrix))
  dframe <- rbind(dframe, data.frame(model=c(name), accuracy=c(accuracy)))
  return(dframe)
}
results12<- data.frame(matrix(ncol = 2, nrow = 0))
